96. Am J Public Health. 2022 Aug;112(8):1151-1160. doi: 10.2105/AJPH.2022.306805.

The (Im)precision of Life Expectancy Numbers.

Hanley JA(1).

Author information:
(1)The author is with the Department of Epidemiology and Biostatistics, McGill 
University, Montreal, Canada.

Life expectancy figures for countries and population segments are increasingly 
being reported to more decimal places and used as indicators of the strengths or 
failings of countries' health and social systems. Reports seldom quantify their 
intrinsic statistical imprecision or the age-specific numbers of deaths that 
determine them. The SE formulas available to compute imprecision are all model 
based. This note adds a more intuitive data-based SE method and extends the 
jackknife to the analysis of event rates more generally. It also describes the 
relationships between the magnitude of the SE and the numbers of person-years 
and deaths on which it is based. These relationships can help quantify the 
statistical noise present in published year-to-year differences in life 
expectancies, as well as in same-year differences between or within countries. 
Agencies and investigators are encouraged to use one of these SEs to report the 
imprecision of life expectancy numbers and to tailor the number of decimal 
places accordingly. (Am J Public Health. 2022;112(8):1151-1160. 
https://doi.org/10.2105/AJPH.2022.306805).

DOI: 10.2105/AJPH.2022.306805
PMCID: PMC9342812
